Cape Town - A new task team set up to develop and pursue a sustainable programme for the management of the Chacma baboon population on the Cape Peninsula, is set to meet within the next two weeks. In a statement on Wednesday, the Department of Forestry, Fisheries and the Environment said various stakeholders have pledged their commitment to finding a lasting solution to the issue on baboon management in the City of Cape Town. “The pledge follows a discussion at the stakeholder engagement in Cape Town led by the Minister Barbara Creecy who was joined by the City of Cape Town Deputy Mayor, Eddie Andrews, SANParks and Cape Nature,” it said. Also in attendance were various interested and affected stakeholders who have committed to ensuring that sustainable solutions to baboon management in Table Mountain National Park, the city and other protected areas are realised. At the meeting, SANParks, Cape Nature and the City agreed to establish a joint Task Team, to develop and pursue the development of a sustainable programme for the management of the baboon population on the Cape Peninsula; and that the first meeting of the task team will happen within the next two weeks. “Baboons occur naturally in the Cape Peninsula and their numbers have grown over the last few decades. “SANParks, Cape Nature and the City have agreed to work towards a Memorandum of Understanding to govern Baboon Management in the Cape Peninsula,” the department said. Creecy urged all the stakeholders to forge a close partnership that will be guided by science and research. Cape Times